---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import ToolPageCta from '../../components/ToolPageCta.astro';
import FaqSection from '../../components/FaqSection.astro';

const faq = [
  {
    question: "What is Apache Kafka and why is it so widely used?",
    answer: "Apache Kafka is a distributed event streaming platform originally built by LinkedIn and open-sourced in 2011. It is designed for high-throughput, fault-tolerant, durable message streaming at massive scale. Kafka stores messages in partitioned, replicated logs on disk, allowing consumers to replay history — a feature no traditional message queue offers. This makes Kafka ideal for event sourcing, activity tracking, log aggregation, stream processing (with Kafka Streams or Apache Flink), and change data capture (CDC). Kafka is the backbone of real-time data infrastructure at companies like Uber, Netflix, Airbnb, and LinkedIn, handling trillions of messages per day. The operational tradeoff: Kafka requires ZooKeeper (legacy) or KRaft (Kafka 3.x) and is complex to tune and operate at scale."
  },
  {
    question: "When should I use RabbitMQ instead of Kafka?",
    answer: "RabbitMQ implements the AMQP protocol and is a traditional message broker with rich routing logic: topic exchanges, direct routing, fanout, and header-based routing. Unlike Kafka's log retention, RabbitMQ deletes messages once they are acknowledged — it is designed for task queues where each message is processed exactly once by one consumer. Use RabbitMQ when you need: complex routing logic between microservices, task queue semantics (background jobs, email sending, image processing), low message volume with complex workflows, or when your team already uses it and doesn't need Kafka's replay capabilities. RabbitMQ is simpler to operate for workloads under ~50k messages/second and integrates natively with Celery, Sidekiq, and most application frameworks."
  },
  {
    question: "What is Redpanda and how does it compare to Kafka?",
    answer: "Redpanda is a Kafka-compatible streaming platform written in C++ (not Java/Scala) with no ZooKeeper or JVM dependency. It implements the Kafka API 100% — any Kafka client works with Redpanda without code changes. The C++ implementation delivers 10x lower tail latencies (p99) and significantly lower resource consumption compared to Apache Kafka for equivalent throughput. Redpanda's built-in Wasm-based transforms, schema registry, and HTTP proxy ship in a single binary. Redpanda Cloud (managed) competes directly with Confluent Cloud. The main tradeoff: smaller ecosystem and community compared to Kafka, and some advanced Kafka features (e.g., certain compaction configurations) have behavioral differences. Ideal for teams wanting Kafka semantics with lower operational overhead."
  },
  {
    question: "Do I need a message queue if I'm already using a database?",
    answer: "For low-volume use cases, a database-backed queue (PostgreSQL SKIP LOCKED, Redis lists, or Amazon SQS) may be sufficient and much simpler to operate. The case for a dedicated message broker emerges when: (1) you need fan-out to multiple consumers simultaneously, (2) message volume exceeds what your database can handle without impacting primary workloads, (3) you need message replay or event sourcing, (4) you need stream processing (aggregations over time windows), or (5) you need to decouple services across different tech stacks or teams. As a rule of thumb: under 10k messages/day, use database queues. Between 10k and 1M/day, evaluate RabbitMQ or Redis Streams. Above 1M/day or with replay requirements, Kafka or Redpanda."
  },
];

const tools = [
  { name: 'Apache Kafka', throughput: 95, latency: 60, ops: 40, ecosystem: 95 },
  { name: 'RabbitMQ', throughput: 55, latency: 90, ops: 80, ecosystem: 75 },
  { name: 'Redpanda', throughput: 98, latency: 95, ops: 70, ecosystem: 50 },
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Apache Kafka vs RabbitMQ vs Redpanda: Message Queue Comparison 2026"
  description="Compare Apache Kafka, RabbitMQ, and Redpanda. Throughput visualization, feature matrix, and use-case picker to choose the right message broker for your architecture."
  tool="Kafka vs RabbitMQ, Redpanda comparison, message queue comparison, event streaming platform, Kafka vs Redpanda, message broker selection"
  faq={faq}
>
  <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold mb-2">Apache Kafka vs RabbitMQ vs Redpanda</h1>
  <p class="text-text-muted mb-4">Three message brokers with fundamentally different architectures. Compare throughput, latency, operational complexity, and ecosystem to pick the right fit.</p>

  <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-6 text-sm text-text-muted flex-wrap">
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> Throughput comparison chart</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> Feature matrix</span>
    <span class="flex items-center gap-1.5"><span class="text-green-500">✓</span> Use-case picker</span>
  </div>

  <!-- Throughput Visualization -->
  <div class="bg-bg-card border border-border rounded-xl p-5 mb-6">
    <h2 class="text-base font-semibold mb-1">Relative Performance Comparison</h2>
    <p class="text-xs text-text-muted mb-4">Relative scores (0–100) based on typical production benchmarks. Actual performance depends heavily on hardware, configuration, and workload characteristics.</p>

    <div class="space-y-5">
      {[
        { label: 'Peak Throughput (msgs/sec)', key: 'throughput', note: 'Kafka/Redpanda: 100M+/sec cluster. RabbitMQ: ~50M/sec.' },
        { label: 'Tail Latency (p99, lower = better score)', key: 'latency', note: 'Redpanda p99 ~1ms. Kafka p99 ~5–15ms. RabbitMQ p99 ~2ms for small msgs.' },
        { label: 'Operational Simplicity', key: 'ops', note: 'RabbitMQ easiest to run. Redpanda single binary. Kafka requires most tuning.' },
        { label: 'Ecosystem & Integrations', key: 'ecosystem', note: 'Kafka has 1000+ connectors. RabbitMQ has AMQP + Stomp. Redpanda is Kafka-compatible.' },
      ].map(({ label, key, note }) => (
        <div>
          <p class="text-xs font-medium mb-2">{label}</p>
          <p class="text-xs text-text-muted mb-2">{note}</p>
          {tools.map(tool => (
            <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-1.5">
              <span class="text-xs text-text-muted w-28 flex-shrink-0">{tool.name}</span>
              <div class="flex-1 bg-border rounded-full h-4 overflow-hidden">
                <div
                  class="h-full rounded-full bg-primary transition-all"
                  style={`width: ${tool[key as keyof typeof tool]}%`}
                ></div>
              </div>
              <span class="text-xs text-text-muted w-8 text-right">{tool[key as keyof typeof tool]}</span>
            </div>
          ))}
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Feature Matrix -->
  <div class="bg-bg-card border border-border rounded-xl p-5 mb-6 overflow-x-auto">
    <h2 class="text-base font-semibold mb-4">Feature Matrix</h2>
    <table class="w-full text-sm min-w-[600px]">
      <thead>
        <tr class="text-text-muted text-xs border-b border-border">
          <th class="text-left pb-3 font-medium w-52">Feature</th>
          <th class="text-center pb-3 font-medium">Kafka</th>
          <th class="text-center pb-3 font-medium">RabbitMQ</th>
          <th class="text-center pb-3 font-medium">Redpanda</th>
        </tr>
      </thead>
      <tbody class="divide-y divide-border text-xs">
        <tr><td class="py-2.5 text-text-muted font-medium">Message replay / history</td><td class="py-2.5 text-center text-green-500">✓</td><td class="py-2.5 text-center text-red-400">✗</td><td class="py-2.5 text-center text-green-500">✓</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="py-2.5 text-text-muted font-medium">Complex routing (exchanges)</td><td class="py-2.5 text-center text-red-400">✗</td><td class="py-2.5 text-center text-green-500">✓ AMQP</td><td class="py-2.5 text-center text-red-400">✗</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="py-2.5 text-text-muted font-medium">Exactly-once delivery</td><td class="py-2.5 text-center text-green-500">✓ (idempotent)</td><td class="py-2.5 text-center text-yellow-500">At-least-once</td><td class="py-2.5 text-center text-green-500">✓</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="py-2.5 text-text-muted font-medium">Built-in stream processing</td><td class="py-2.5 text-center text-green-500">Kafka Streams</td><td class="py-2.5 text-center text-red-400">✗</td><td class="py-2.5 text-center text-yellow-500">Wasm transforms</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="py-2.5 text-text-muted font-medium">Schema registry</td><td class="py-2.5 text-center text-yellow-500">Confluent (paid)</td><td class="py-2.5 text-center text-red-400">✗</td><td class="py-2.5 text-center text-green-500">Built-in</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="py-2.5 text-text-muted font-medium">ZooKeeper / external deps</td><td class="py-2.5 text-center text-yellow-500">KRaft (3.x, no ZK)</td><td class="py-2.5 text-center text-green-500">None</td><td class="py-2.5 text-center text-green-500">None</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="py-2.5 text-text-muted font-medium">Managed cloud offering</td><td class="py-2.5 text-center">Confluent Cloud / MSK</td><td class="py-2.5 text-center">CloudAMQP / AWS MQ</td><td class="py-2.5 text-center">Redpanda Cloud</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="py-2.5 text-text-muted font-medium">Language / Protocol</td><td class="py-2.5 text-center">Java / Kafka protocol</td><td class="py-2.5 text-center">Erlang / AMQP</td><td class="py-2.5 text-center">C++ / Kafka protocol</td></tr>
        <tr><td class="py-2.5 text-text-muted font-medium">Open Source</td><td class="py-2.5 text-center text-green-500">✓ Apache 2.0</td><td class="py-2.5 text-center text-green-500">✓ Mozilla 2.0</td><td class="py-2.5 text-center text-green-500">✓ BSL / SSPL</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>
  </div>

  <!-- Use-case Picker -->
  <div class="bg-bg-card border border-border rounded-xl p-5 mb-6">
    <h2 class="text-base font-semibold mb-3">Use-Case Picker</h2>
    <div class="space-y-2 mb-4">
      {[
        { label: 'Event sourcing / audit log', tool: 'Kafka or Redpanda' },
        { label: 'Background job queue (email, image resize)', tool: 'RabbitMQ' },
        { label: 'Real-time analytics pipeline', tool: 'Kafka or Redpanda' },
        { label: 'Microservice task routing (complex exchanges)', tool: 'RabbitMQ' },
        { label: 'Change data capture (CDC) from databases', tool: 'Kafka (Debezium)' },
        { label: 'Low-latency trading / fintech streaming', tool: 'Redpanda' },
        { label: 'Log aggregation at scale', tool: 'Kafka' },
        { label: 'Simple pub/sub between services', tool: 'RabbitMQ or Redis Streams' },
      ].map(({ label, tool }) => (
        <div class="flex items-center justify-between py-2 border-b border-border last:border-0">
          <span class="text-xs text-text-muted">{label}</span>
          <span class="text-xs font-medium text-primary bg-primary/10 px-2 py-0.5 rounded">{tool}</span>
        </div>
      ))}
    </div>
    <p class="text-xs text-text-muted bg-bg-card border border-border rounded-lg p-3">
      <strong class="text-foreground">Rule of thumb:</strong> If you need message history/replay, pick Kafka or Redpanda. If you need complex routing or task-queue semantics, pick RabbitMQ. If you want Kafka semantics with lower resource usage and single-binary deployment, pick Redpanda.
    </p>
  </div>

  <FaqSection faq={faq} />
  <ToolPageCta currentTool="Kafka vs RabbitMQ vs Redpanda" relatedTags={['kafka', 'rabbitmq', 'redpanda', 'message-queue', 'event-streaming', 'pub-sub', 'microservices', 'data-engineering']} />
</BaseLayout>
